"]}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"div\\\",null,{\\\"className\\\":\\\"tracking-wide\\\",\\\"children\\\":\\\"MICHIGAN GUIDED HUNTS · LAKE HURON CHARTER FISHING\\\"}]]}]\\na:[\\\"$\\\",\\\"$1\\\",\\\"c\\\",{\\\"children\\\":[null,[\\\"$\\\",\\\"$L3\\\",null,{\\\"parallelRouterKey\\\":\\\"children\\\",\\\"error\\\":\\\"$undefined\\\",\\\"errorStyles\\\":\\\"$undefined\\\",\\\"errorScripts\\\":\\\"$undefined\\\",\\\"template\\\":[\\\"$\\\",\\\"$L4\\\",null,{}],\\\"templateStyles\\\":\\\"$undefined\\\",\\\"templateScripts\\\":\\\"$undefined\\\",\\\"notFound\\\":\\\"$undefined\\\",\\\"forbidden\\\":\\\"$undefined\\\",\\\"unauthorized\\\":\\\"$undefined\\\"}]]}]\\nb:[\\\"$\\\",\\\"$1\\\",\\\"c\\\",{\\\"children\\\":[null,[\\\"$\\\",\\\"$L3\\\",null,{\\\"parallelRouterKey\\\":\\\"children\\\",\\\"error\\\":\\\"$undefined\\\",\\\"errorStyles\\\":\\\"$undefined\\\",\\\"errorScripts\\\":\\\"$undefined\\\",\\\"template\\\":[\\\"$\\\",\\\"$L4\\\",null,{}],\\\"templateStyles\\\":\\\"$undefined\\\",\\\"templateScripts\\\":\\\"$undefined\\\",\\\"notFound\\\":\\\"$undefined\\\",\\\"forbidden\\\":\\\"$undefined\\\",\\\"unauthorized\\\":\\\"$undefined\\\"}]]}]\\nc:[\\\"\"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,\"$\\\",\\\"$1\\\",\\\"c\\\",{\\\"children\\\":[\\\"$L12\\\",[[\\\"$\\\",\\\"script\\\",\\\"script-0\\\",{\\\"src\\\":\\\"/_next/static/chunks/0lnjlo~xn6fto.js\\\",\\\"async\\\":true,\\\"nonce\\\":\\\"$undefined\\\"}]],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"$L13\\\",null,{\\\"children\\\":[\\\"$\\\",\\\"$14\\\",null,{\\\"name\\\":\\\"Next.MetadataOutlet\\\",\\\"children\\\":\\\"$@15\\\"}]}]]}]\\n16:[]\\nd:\\\"$W16\\\"\\ne:[\\\"$\\\",\\\"$1\\\",\\\"h\\\",{\\\"children\\\":[null,[\\\"$\\\",\\\"$L17\\\",null,{\\\"children\\\":\\\"$L18\\\"}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"div\\\",null,{\\\"hidden\\\":true,\\\"children\\\":[\\\"$\\\",\\\"$L19\\\",null,{\\\"children\\\":[\\\"$\\\",\\\"$14\\\",null,{\\\"name\\\":\\\"Next.Metadata\\\",\\\"children\\\":\\\"$L1a\\\"}]}]}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"meta\\\",null,{\\\"name\\\":\\\"next-size-adjust\\\",\\\"content\\\":\\\"\\\"}]]}]\\n10:[\\\"$\\\",\\\"link\\\",\\\"0\\\",{\\\"rel\\\":\\\"stylesheet\\\",\\\"href\\\":\\\"/_next/static/chunks/0npi_rp6qs2dq.css\\\",\\\"precedence\\\":\\\"next\\\",\\\"crossOrigin\\\":\\\"$undefined\\\",\\\"nonce\\\":\\\"$undefined\\\"}]\\n\"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,\"1b:I[85437,[\\\"/_next/static/chunks/04hm9vf8xmubm.js\\\",\\\"/_next/static/chunks/0y-.2i-zv25eo.js\\\",\\\"/_next/static/chunks/0~a.u3-2ydpng.js\\\",\\\"/_next/static/chunks/0d3shmwh5_nmn.js\\\",\\\"/_next/static/chunks/0lnjlo~xn6fto.js\\\"],\\\"Image\\\"]\\n1c:I[59095,[\\\"/_next/static/chunks/04hm9vf8xmubm.js\\\",\\\"/_next/static/chunks/0y-.2i-zv25eo.js\\\",\\\"/_next/static/chunks/0~a.u3-2ydpng.js\\\",\\\"/_next/static/chunks/0d3shmwh5_nmn.js\\\",\\\"/_next/static/chunks/0lnjlo~xn6fto.js\\\"],\\\"Reveal\\\"]\\n1d:T32d0,\"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,\"\\u003ch1\\u003eDuck Hunting in Michigan's Thumb — Guided Hunts with Hotshot Outfitters\\u003c/h1\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eMichigan's Thumb punches above its weight in duck hunting, and most hunters driving through Huron County on their way to deer camp have no idea what they're missing. The Lake Huron shoreline, coastal marshes, flooded agricultural fields, and inland potholes that define this landscape are a flyway intersection — ducks moving south from Lake Huron's Canadian shore stack up here, and the divers running the big-water highway along the coast produce action that you won't find fifty miles inland. Hotshot Outfitters guides duck hunts in Michigan's Thumb, and 20+ years of working this specific waterscape means our guides know exactly where birds want to be.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eThis page covers everything you need to know about booking a guided duck hunt with us in Port Hope and the surrounding Huron County area.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003chr\\u003e\\n\\u003ch2\\u003eWhy Lake Huron's Thumb Coast Is a Duck Hunting Destination\\u003c/h2\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eDuck hunters in Michigan tend to concentrate in the Saginaw Bay area, the Upper Peninsula, and the St. Clair Flats. Those are all excellent destinations. But the eastern Lake Huron coastline through Huron County is consistently overlooked, and that oversight works in our favor.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eThe geography here puts you in front of multiple duck hunting opportunities simultaneously. The Lake Huron shoreline provides access to diving duck flights — bluebills (scaup), buffleheads, redheads, ring-necks, canvasbacks, goldeneye, and long-tailed ducks — that move along the coast during the fall migration. Divers work different than puddlers: they raft offshore, respond to big decoy spreads with confidence lines, and when conditions push them inshore, the shooting can be explosive.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eInland from the shoreline, the agricultural fields and pothole wetlands of Huron County hold resident and migrating puddle ducks — mallards, teal, wood ducks, black ducks, and wigeon. These birds work the grain fields and flooded corn edges, and hunting them requires a completely different approach: smaller decoy spreads, tighter concealment, and an understanding of feeding patterns.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eThe marsh and wetland fringe along shoreline drainages adds a third dimension: brushy creek mouths, cattail stands, and emergent wetland edges that hold mallards, teal, and black ducks in numbers that would surprise hunters unfamiliar with this coast.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003chr\\u003e\\n\\u003ch2\\u003eMichigan Duck Season Dates and Framework\\u003c/h2\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eDuck seasons in Michigan are set cooperatively by the U.S. Fish \\u0026#x26; Wildlife Service and the MI DNR under the Migratory Bird Treaty Act framework. Season dates, species-specific bag limits, and regulations are established annually — dates shift year to year based on population assessments.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eAs a general planning reference for Michigan:\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cul\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eRegular Duck Season\\u003c/strong\\u003e: Typically opens in early to mid-October and runs through late November or early December, depending on the zone (Michigan splits into North, South, and Restricted zones)\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eTeal Season\\u003c/strong\\u003e: Often a separate early teal-only season in September\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eDaily Bag Limits\\u003c/strong\\u003e: Species-specific and set annually — typically a mixed bag limit of six ducks per day with species-specific sub-limits; always verify current limits before hunting\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eNon-Toxic Shot\\u003c/strong\\u003e: Required for all waterfowl hunting in Michigan (steel, bismuth, TSS, etc.)\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003c/ul\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eHuron County falls under Michigan's specific waterfowl zone designations. The MI DNR publishes a comprehensive waterfowl guide annually that covers zone boundaries, open dates, and bag limits.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eAlways verify current season dates and regulations at the \\u003ca href=\\\"https://www.michigan.gov/dnr\\\"\\u003eMI DNR website\\u003c/a\\u003e and the U.S. Fish \\u0026#x26; Wildlife Service migratory bird regulations before your hunt.\\u003c/strong\\u003e Waterfowl regulations are among the most complex in hunting, and they change every year. Your guide will be current on regulations for your hunt date, but you are responsible for knowing the rules.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003chr\\u003e\\n\\u003ch2\\u003eWhat to Expect on a Guided Duck Hunt\\u003c/h2\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eDuck hunting with Hotshot Outfitters is built around the conditions we'll face on your hunt day. A cold front pushing birds south, a clear bluebird day with still air, or an overcast morning with northwest wind — each requires a different approach. Our guides have 20+ years of reading Lake Huron's weather and water conditions, and that translates into better calls about where to be and how to set up.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003ePre-Hunt\\u003c/strong\\u003e: Guides scout conditions and bird activity in the days before your hunt. We'll discuss what we're seeing — whether divers are working the shoreline, whether puddle ducks are hitting a particular cut corn field, or whether marsh hunting makes the most sense given water levels and bird distribution.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eSetup\\u003c/strong\\u003e: Depending on the target species and conditions, we'll be setting up in a layout boat, blind, or marsh hide. Diver hunting on Lake Huron may involve a shore or jetty setup with large decoy spreads. Puddle duck hunting in fields or pothole marshes involves pit blinds or natural-material field blinds with smaller, realistic decoy configurations.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eCalling\\u003c/strong\\u003e: Mallard calling is a skill that makes a significant difference in close-range puddle duck hunting. Diver hunting typically relies more on the decoy spread and location than aggressive calling. Your guide will manage the calling sequence and will coach you if you want to learn.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eDog Work\\u003c/strong\\u003e: If you're hunting with a retriever, we can discuss how to integrate your dog into the hunt setup. Well-trained retrievers are welcome — confirm at booking.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003chr\\u003e\\n\\u003ch2\\u003eDiver Ducks vs. Puddle Ducks: Two Different Hunts\\u003c/h2\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eIt's worth explaining the distinction because the hunts are genuinely different in character.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eDiver Hunting on Lake Huron\\u003c/strong\\u003e: Setting up points, jetties, or shore positions with large decoy spreads extended out into the lake. Divers raft in open water and fly with speed and confidence — they don't hover and drop like mallards; they come in low, fast, and committed. The shooting is challenging in a different way. When a raft of bluebills decides to work your spread on a gray October morning, the pace is relentless.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003ePuddle Duck Hunting in Fields and Marshes\\u003c/strong\\u003e: Working cut corn, flooded fields, pothole marshes, and creek mouth locations for mallards, blacks, teal, and wood ducks. These hunts are about reading daily feeding patterns and being in the right place when the birds move in the morning. Mallards on a late October morning dropping into flooded corn with a northwest wind behind them is a Michigan duck hunting experience worth traveling for.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eWe guide both types of hunts. Tell us what you're after and we'll put together the right hunt for you.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003chr\\u003e\\n\\u003ch2\\u003eLicensing and Federal Duck Stamp Requirements\\u003c/h2\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eEvery waterfowl hunter in Michigan must hold:\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cul\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eValid Michigan Hunting License\\u003c/strong\\u003e with a \\u003cstrong\\u003eMichigan Duck Stamp\\u003c/strong\\u003e (waterfowl base license requirement)\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eFederal Duck Stamp\\u003c/strong\\u003e — required for all waterfowl hunters 16 and older; available at USPS offices, license agents, and online at the USFWS website\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eNon-residents must purchase appropriate non-resident Michigan licenses\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003c/ul\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eWaterfowl hunting requires more licensing than most hunting — both state and federal requirements apply. Do not arrive without both your Michigan hunting license/duck stamp and your federal duck stamp. There are no exceptions and no workarounds.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003chr\\u003e\\n\\u003ch2\\u003eWhat We Supply vs. What You Bring\\u003c/h2\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eHotshot Outfitters provides:\\u003c/strong\\u003e\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cul\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eGuide with 20+ years of Michigan waterfowl hunting experience\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eDecoy spreads (diver and/or puddle configurations as applicable)\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eBlind or boat setup for your hunt type\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eCalling\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eScouted locations on private and public-access waterways and ag fields\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003c/ul\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eYou bring:\\u003c/strong\\u003e\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cul\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eValid Michigan hunting license with duck stamp, and federal duck stamp\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eShotgun — 12-gauge or 20-gauge with non-toxic shot capability\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eNon-toxic shotgun shells: steel, bismuth, or TSS (#3 or #2 steel for mallards and divers; smaller shot for teal; confirm your load selection based on target species)\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eWaterproof waders (neoprene or breathable depending on season) and waterproof jacket\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eWarm layering — October and November mornings on Lake Huron are cold and can be brutally windy\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eFacemask and gloves — concealment on flat water setups is critical\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003ePersonal dog if desired (confirm at booking)\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003c/ul\\u003e\\n\\u003chr\\u003e\\n\\u003ch2\\u003eGear Notes for Michigan Duck Hunting\\u003c/h2\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eLake Huron in October and November is not a comfortable place to be underdressed. Wind-driven rain, cold temperatures, and the spray off chop on the lake combine in ways that cut through lighter clothing fast. Waterproof bibs and a waterproof jacket with seam sealing are not optional. Neoprene waders or quality breathable waders with appropriate insulation underneath are the baseline for marsh and shoreline setups.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eFor shotgun loads, Michigan waterfowl require non-toxic shot. Steel is the most common choice. For diver ducks — which are dense-feathered birds typically taken at longer ranges — #2 or #3 steel in a 3\\\" or 3.5\\\" shell provides the pattern density needed. For close-range marsh mallards, #4 or #3 steel works well. Modern premium non-toxic loads (bismuth, HEAVYWEIGHT, TSS) perform closer to lead at lower shot sizes — if you're willing to invest in premium loads, they're worth it.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eModified or improved modified choke is the standard for steel shot in 12-gauge. Do not shoot steel through full choke — it will damage the barrel.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003chr\\u003e\\n\\u003ch2\\u003eFrequently Asked Questions\\u003c/h2\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eQ: Do I need a Federal Duck Stamp to hunt ducks in Michigan?\\u003c/strong\\u003e\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eYes. All waterfowl hunters 16 and older must possess a valid Federal Migratory Bird Hunting and Conservation Stamp (Federal Duck Stamp) in addition to their state license. It is available online at the USFWS website, at USPS locations, and at many sporting goods stores.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eQ: What species of ducks are common on Lake Huron's Thumb coast?\\u003c/strong\\u003e\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eThe coastal diver flight includes scaup (bluebills), buffleheads, ring-necked ducks, redheads, goldeneye, and long-tailed ducks (oldsquaw). Inland and marsh hunting adds mallards, black ducks, teal (early season), wood ducks, and wigeon to the mix. Species composition and abundance varies by year and weather conditions.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eQ: What kind of weather produces the best duck hunting in Michigan's Thumb?\\u003c/strong\\u003e\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eCold fronts from the northwest produce the best duck movement, particularly for divers along the Lake Huron coast. A two- or three-day blow followed by clearing skies and northwest wind will push migrating birds and concentrate them along the shoreline. Overcast, calm mornings are often good for marsh and field hunting where calling keeps birds engaged.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eQ: Can I hunt ducks with lead shot in Michigan?\\u003c/strong\\u003e\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eNo. Non-toxic shot is federally mandated for all waterfowl hunting in the United States. Steel shot is the standard; bismuth, TSS, and other approved non-toxic alternatives are legal but more expensive. Your guide will confirm what you need.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eQ: Do you guide early teal season hunts in Michigan?\\u003c/strong\\u003e\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eAsk us when you book. Early teal season is typically a short September window — dates vary by year. If teal season overlaps with our available guide schedule, we can discuss putting together a teal-specific hunt.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eQ: What is the daily bag limit for ducks in Michigan?\\u003c/strong\\u003e\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eBag limits are set annually under the Migratory Bird Treaty framework and are species-specific. A combined daily bag limit of six ducks per day is the general federal framework, with sub-limits on specific species (canvasback, redhead, pintail, etc.). Verify current limits at the MI DNR and USFWS websites before your hunt — limits change year to year.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003chr\\u003e\\n\\u003ch2\\u003eBook Your Michigan Duck Hunt\\u003c/h2\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eDuck hunting in Michigan's Thumb — from diver flights on Lake Huron to mallards working a flooded corn field — is world-class hunting that too few hunters have discovered. Hotshot Outfitters has spent 20+ years learning every marsh edge, shoreline point, and feeding field in this corner of Michigan. We're ready to put you in the right spot when the birds are moving.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eContact us to check season availability and current conditions.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003ePhone:\\u003c/strong\\u003e (989) 551-4551 or (989) 670-4336\\n\\u003cstrong\\u003eAddress:\\u003c/strong\\u003e 6900 Huron City Road, Port Hope, MI 48468\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eDuck season doesn't last. Get on the schedule while spots are open.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,\"12:[[\\\"$\\\",\\\"script\\\",null,{\\\"type\\\":\\\"application/ld+json\\\",\\\"dangerouslySetInnerHTML\\\":{\\\"__html\\\":\\\"{\\\\\\\"@context\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"https://schema.org\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"@type\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"Article\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"headline\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"Duck Hunting in Michigan | Guided Hunts with Hotshot Outfitters\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"description\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"Guided duck hunting in Michigan's Thumb on Lake Huron with Hotshot Outfitters. Diver ducks, puddle ducks, marsh hunting. Port Hope, Huron County, 20+ yrs experience.\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"image\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"https://hotshotoutfitters.com/images/michigan-hunting-duck-waterfowl-michigan-01.webp\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"author\\\\\\\":{\\\\\\\"@type\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"Organization\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"name\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"Hotshot Outfitters\\\\\\\"},\\\\\\\"publisher\\\\\\\":{\\\\\\\"@type\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"Organization\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"name\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"Hotshot Outfitters\\\\\\\"},\\\\\\\"mainEntityOfPage\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"https://hotshotoutfitters.com/hunts/duck\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"about\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"Duck hunting in Michigan\\\\\\\"}\\\"}}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"section\\\",null,{\\\"className\\\":\\\"relative pt-32 pb-16 lg:pt-40 lg:pb-24 overflow-hidden\\\",\\\"children\\\":[[\\\"$\\\",\\\"$L1b\\\",null,{\\\"src\\\":\\\"/images/michigan-hunting-duck-waterfowl-michigan-01.webp\\\",\\\"alt\\\":\\\"Michigan duck hunting limit from a Lak